I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve data from the API endpoint as the first step in the workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll modify the network_fetcher call to specify XML format in the options parameter, as indicated by the error message.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {
    "format": "xml"
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I'll proceed with the data_processing_validator tool to validate the data retrieved from the network_fetcher. Since the validator requires a schema, I'll use a default validation schema.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {
    "data": []
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll proceed with the final step of the workflow, which is data parsing. I'll use the data_processing_parser tool to structure the data.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/output.json",
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I'll retry the data_processing_parser with XML format since we previously received XML data from the network_fetcher.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/output.xml",
  "options": {
    "format": "xml"
  }
}
</tool_call>
